definitions: having a lower position or rank in an organization or profession
being younger in age when comparing two people with same name
designed for or relating to young people or children in education
examples: She works as a junior analyst at the bank
The junior officers must report to senior management
Robert Smith Junior is named after his father
My junior brother just started high school
The store sells junior clothing sizes for teenagers
He coaches the junior basketball team on weekends

definitions: attractive in a pretty or endearing way that inspires affection
showing cleverness or shrewdness in a playful or annoying manner
examples: The puppy looked so cute with its floppy ears
She wore a cute dress to the birthday party
Don't get cute with me about following rules
His cute remarks during the meeting annoyed everyone

definitions: relating to the human mind and its functions, especially those affecting behavior
affecting or arising in the mind rather than from physical causes
examples: The patient underwent psychological testing before treatment began
She's studying psychological theories about child development
The team used psychological tactics to intimidate their opponents
Living alone can have psychological effects on elderly people

definitions: existing in an extreme degree with very strong force or strength
showing or feeling very strong emotions or opinions about something
requiring complete focus and demanding great effort or concentration
examples: The intense heat made it difficult to work outside
She felt intense pain in her injured shoulder
He's an intense person who feels everything deeply
Their intense rivalry lasted throughout their careers
The training program involves intense physical and mental challenges
Learning a new language requires intense study and practice

definitions: showing kindness and warmth in attitude or behavior toward others
not causing harm or damage and safe to use or approach
having an informal, relaxed atmosphere that makes people feel comfortable
examples: The staff at the hotel were very friendly
She gave me a friendly smile when we met
This software has a user-friendly interface design
We only use eco-friendly cleaning products at home
The restaurant has a friendly atmosphere for families
It was just a friendly game between neighbors

definitions: feeling or showing the need or desire to eat food
having a strong desire or craving for something beyond food
examples: The children were hungry after playing all afternoon
I'm too hungry to concentrate on work now
The company is hungry for success in new markets
She's hungry for knowledge and reads constantly

definitions: causing someone to feel hurt, angry, or upset by being rude or insulting
actively attacking or aggressive in sports, war, or competition
relating to the act of attacking or scoring in games and sports
examples: His offensive comments about women upset many people
The comedian's jokes were too offensive for television
The army launched an offensive strike against enemy positions
Their offensive strategy overwhelmed the defending team
The coach focused on improving their offensive plays
He plays an offensive position on the football team

definitions: used or intended to defend or protect from attack or harm
anxious to challenge or avoid criticism by justifying one's actions
examples: The castle had strong defensive walls against invaders
Players practiced defensive moves to block their opponents
She became defensive when asked about her mistakes
His defensive attitude made the conversation difficult

definitions: relating to Asia or its countries, peoples, customs, or languages
being a person whose family originally comes from Asia
examples: The museum features ancient Asian art and artifacts
She studied Asian history at the university
The neighborhood has many Asian families and businesses
He's proud of his Asian heritage and culture

definitions: lasting or intended to last forever without change or end
existing or continuing for a long time without being temporary
examples: The accident left permanent damage to his hearing
They made permanent changes to the company structure
She finally got a permanent job after years of contracts
The museum has both permanent and temporary exhibitions

definitions: available as another possibility or choice instead of something else
different from the usual or traditional way of doing things
examples: We need an alternative plan if this doesn't work
The doctor suggested alternative treatments for her condition
She listens to alternative rock music instead of pop
The school offers alternative education methods for gifted students

definitions: completely correct in every detail without any mistakes or differences
very careful and accurate about details in actions or requirements
examples: I need the exact measurements before cutting the wood
No one knows the exact number of stars in space
The recipe requires exact timing for perfect results
She's very exact about following all the rules

definitions: applying to all people or things in the world or in a group
present or occurring everywhere in the world or universe
examples: Access to clean water should be a universal right
Love is a universal theme in literature and art
Scientists search for universal laws governing nature
Smartphones have become universal in modern society

definitions: extremely important or necessary for success or for something to happen
happening at a critical moment when things might go very badly or well
examples: Good communication is crucial for healthy relationships
It's crucial that we arrive before the meeting starts
The next few days will be crucial for negotiations
She scored the crucial goal in the final minute

definitions: deserving to be laughed at or mocked because of being foolish
extremely unreasonable or unsuitable to the point of being absurd
examples: He looked ridiculous wearing that tiny hat
The movie's plot was so ridiculous we couldn't stop laughing
They're asking a ridiculous price for that old car
It's ridiculous to expect me to work without pay

definitions: quick to detect or respond to slight changes, signals, or influences
aware of and understanding other people's feelings and needs
requiring careful treatment because easily damaged or likely to cause problems
containing information that must be kept secret for security reasons
examples: My skin is sensitive to certain types of soap
The equipment is sensitive enough to detect tiny movements
She's very sensitive to her students' emotional needs
A good therapist must be sensitive and compassionate
This is a sensitive topic that requires careful discussion
Handle the antique vase carefully as it's very sensitive
The government classified the sensitive documents immediately
They discussed sensitive information in a secure room

definitions: at or forming the lowest part or base of something
having the lowest rank or least importance in a hierarchy
examples: The signature goes at the bottom of the page
Fish feed near the bottom of the lake
He started at the bottom and worked his way up
Their team finished in bottom place this season

definitions: relating to a country's constitution or its principles of government
relating to someone's physical or mental condition and general health
examples: The court ruled the law was not constitutional
Citizens have constitutional rights to free speech
She takes daily constitutional walks for her health
The doctor said it was a constitutional weakness

definitions: relating to genes or the study of heredity and variation
passed from parents to children through genes rather than learned
examples: Scientists are studying genetic causes of the disease
The lab performs genetic testing on DNA samples
Eye color is a genetic trait from your parents
Some people have a genetic predisposition to diabetes

definitions: connected with or having a relationship to something else mentioned
belonging to the same family by blood or marriage connections
examples: All the incidents were related to the same cause
She asked several questions related to the assignment
Are you related to the famous author John Smith
The two suspects are related through marriage

definitions: being or happening at the end of a process as final
the best, greatest, or most extreme example of its kind
examples: Death is the ultimate fate of all living things
The ultimate decision rests with the board of directors
This car is the ultimate in luxury and comfort
Winning the championship was his ultimate achievement

definitions: not known or identified by anyone with no information available
not famous or recognized by the general public or many people
examples: The cause of the fire remains unknown to investigators
Explorers ventured into unknown territories
The painting was by an unknown artist from the Renaissance
She was completely unknown before winning the competition

definitions: famous or important in history and likely to be remembered
belonging to or concerning the past, especially the distant past
examples: The president made a historic speech about civil rights
They signed a historic peace agreement ending the war
We visited historic buildings from the colonial period
The museum displays historic artifacts from ancient civilizations

definitions: having an uneven or irregular surface that is not smooth
violent or boisterous in behavior, manner, or movement
not exact but close enough to be useful for estimates
characterized by hardship, discomfort, or difficult living conditions
examples: The rough texture of sandpaper helps remove paint
We drove carefully on the rough mountain road
The security guards were rough with the protesters
He grew up in a rough neighborhood with high crime
Give me a rough estimate of the project cost
I have a rough idea of what happened
They had a rough time during the economic recession
Camping can be rough without proper equipment

definitions: relating to or belonging to a king, queen, or their family
impressively grand, magnificent, or suitable for royalty in quality
examples: The royal family attended the state ceremony
Guards protect the royal palace day and night
They gave us the royal treatment at the hotel
The yacht was fitted with royal luxury throughout

definitions: covered or saturated with water or another liquid substance
characterized by rain or the presence of moisture in weather
not yet dry or solid, especially of paint, ink, or cement
examples: Her clothes were wet from walking in the rain
Use a wet cloth to clean the table surface
It's been a wet summer with rain most days
The wet climate is perfect for growing rice
Be careful, the paint is still wet on the fence
The wet cement needs time to set properly

definitions: not cooked and in the natural state without heat applied
in the natural state without being processed or refined
red and painful from skin damage or irritation
new to an activity and lacking experience or skill
examples: Some people enjoy eating raw fish in sushi
Never eat raw chicken as it's dangerous
The factory processes raw materials into finished products
Artists work with raw clay to create pottery
His hands were raw from working without gloves
The cold wind made her face feel raw
The raw recruits needed extensive military training
She showed raw talent but lacked technique

definitions: located inside or toward the center of something
relating to private thoughts, feelings, or the spiritual side
examples: The inner walls of the building need repainting
She lives in the inner city near downtown
Meditation helps you connect with your inner self
He struggled with inner conflicts about his decision

definitions: having progressed or developed to a high or complex level
far along in progress, time, or course of development
examples: The hospital uses advanced medical technology for surgery
She's taking an advanced course in mathematics
The disease was already in an advanced stage
Workers completed the advanced phases of construction

definitions: not likely to happen, be done, or be true with low probability
not what you would expect in an unusual or surprising combination
examples: It's unlikely that it will rain in the desert
She's unlikely to change her mind about moving
They made an unlikely pair as business partners
The movie tells the unlikely story of their friendship

definitions: causing or likely to cause horror, fear, or shock
very bad, unpleasant, or of poor quality in any way
examples: The accident scene was too horrible to describe
She had horrible nightmares about the incident
The food at that restaurant was absolutely horrible
What horrible weather we're having this week

definitions: having paid employment or actively engaged in a job
functioning or operating properly as designed or intended
used for or relating to work rather than leisure
examples: Both parents are working to support the family
The working population pays taxes to fund services
Is your phone working after you dropped it
We need a working solution to this problem
She changed from party clothes into working attire
The farm uses working dogs to herd sheep

definitions: continuing to exist or develop without reaching an end
happening or developing now and expected to continue
examples: The police investigation is ongoing and may take months
There's an ongoing debate about climate change policy
We have ongoing projects that need constant attention
The company faces ongoing challenges in the market

definitions: relating to Mexico, its people, or their language
relating to the culture, food, or traditions originating from Mexico
examples: The Mexican government announced new trade policies
She's learning to speak Mexican Spanish fluently
We enjoyed authentic Mexican food at the restaurant
The festival celebrates Mexican art and music

definitions: having an even and regular surface free from bumps or ridges
happening without problems, difficulties, or delays in progress
moving or operating in a gentle, flowing way without sudden changes
examples: The baby's skin felt smooth and soft
Sand the wood until it's perfectly smooth
The project had a smooth transition between phases
Everything went smooth during the wedding ceremony
The car provides a smooth ride on highways
She made smooth movements while dancing

definitions: clearly visible or understood and obvious to see or comprehend
seeming real or true but not necessarily so
examples: The damage to the car was immediately apparent
It's apparent that she needs help with the project
Despite his apparent confidence, he was quite nervous
The apparent success hid underlying financial problems

definitions: giving off or reflecting much light and shining very brightly
exceptionally clever, talented, or intelligent in ability or performance
outstanding or exceptional in quality, skill, or magnificence
examples: The brilliant sunshine made everyone squint their eyes
Stars appeared brilliant in the clear night sky
She's a brilliant scientist who won the Nobel Prize
His brilliant mind solved problems others couldn't
The pianist gave a brilliant performance last night
That's a brilliant idea for solving our problem

definitions: ready or likely to attack, confront, or use force
pursuing aims forcefully and energetically sometimes excessively
examples: The aggressive dog barked at every passerby
His aggressive behavior made others feel threatened
The company took an aggressive approach to marketing
She's an aggressive negotiator who fights for deals

definitions: having a great deal of money, resources, or assets
having an abundance of valuable resources or qualities
examples: The wealthy businessman donated millions to charity
Only wealthy families could afford private school tuition
The region is wealthy in natural mineral deposits
She comes from a wealthy tradition of storytelling

definitions: eager to know or learn something new through interest
strange, unusual, or unexpected in an interesting way
examples: Children are naturally curious about how things work
She was curious to see what would happen next
He noticed a curious pattern in the data
What a curious coincidence meeting you here

definitions: relating to the basic elements or principles of a subject
relating to or denoting the first years of school education
examples: Students must understand elementary mathematics before advancing
This is elementary knowledge that everyone should have
My daughter attends elementary school in our neighborhood
He teaches elementary grade students aged six to twelve

definitions: specified, stated, or fixed as a fact or assumption beforehand
having a tendency or inclination to do something regularly
examples: You must complete the task within the given timeframe
Under given circumstances, this was the best option
He's given to exaggeration when telling stories
She's not given to complaining about problems

definitions: of considerable importance, size, value, or worth in quantity
strongly built or made and unlikely to break or fail
examples: They made substantial progress on the construction project
The company reported substantial profits this quarter
The house has substantial brick walls for durability

definitions: relating to biology or living organisms and their life processes
related by blood rather than by adoption or marriage
examples: Scientists study biological processes in living cells
The lake's biological diversity supports many species
She finally met her biological parents last year
Biological siblings share genetic traits from parents

definitions: growing, changing, or becoming more advanced over a period
used to describe countries working toward economic advancement
examples: The developing storm threatens the coastal region
Technology is rapidly developing in this field
Many developing nations need better healthcare systems
International aid helps developing countries build infrastructure

definitions: extremely bad, unpleasant, or of very poor quality
inspiring awe or wonder, especially through being impressive
examples: The movie was awful and we left early
She felt awful about forgetting his birthday

definitions: feeling or showing certainty about one's abilities or qualities
feeling or showing certainty that something will happen as expected
examples: She walked into the interview feeling confident and prepared
A confident speaker engages the audience effectively
I'm confident we'll finish the project on time
The team felt confident about winning the championship

definitions: relating to the planning and directing of military operations
carefully designed or planned to serve a particular purpose or advantage
examples: The general made strategic decisions about troop deployment
Countries form strategic alliances for mutual defense
The company made strategic investments in new technology
This is a strategic location for our new office

definitions: relating to or found in the sea or ocean
relating to shipping or naval matters, especially military
examples: Marine biologists study ocean ecosystems and sea life
The aquarium displays various marine creatures
He served in the marine corps for ten years
The marine patrol guards the coastal waters

definitions: equipped with or carrying weapons for attack or defense
having or provided with equipment, tools, or resources needed
examples: Armed guards protect the bank vault at night
The suspect was armed and considered dangerous
Armed with new information, she confronted her boss
